# Ecosystem analyzer (local run)

Goal: run ecosystem-analyzer locally for a single project and collect the JSON output, using a local ty repo/worktree.

## Inputs to gather
- Project name (e.g., scipy)

The remaining inputs are derived automatically from the current jj worktree:
- Output JSON path (use /tmp)

## Commands

1. The `eco` command (in $HOME/bin) will do all the work of running
   ecosystem-analyzer locally. Run it from root directory of a jj workspace. It
   will build and run ty from the current commit. You provide the project that
   should be tested as an argument. The `-o` option tells `eco` where to place
   the JSON file containing all of the diagnostics.

   ```sh
   eco -o /tmp/<project>-ecosystem.json <project>
   ```

2. Read timing from the output JSON:
   ```sh
   rg -n "time_s" /tmp/<project>-ecosystem.json | tail -n 5
   ```

   The `time_s` field will contain the time needed to perform type checking. It
   does not include any overhead time — e.g. from compiling `ty`.

Available additional command line options:

- `-m` Runs ty from the `main` branch instead of from the current commit of the
  checked-out branch.

- `-t <profile>` Use a custom cargo profile. You should rarely need this, since
  `eco` will compile its own isolated copy of ty using the default `profiling`
  profile (which ensures that we compile with optimizations enabled).

## Notes
- Assumes execution from a jj worktree.
- As a side effect, `eco` will clone the project locally into
  `~/.cache/ecosystem-analyzer`. This is useful if you need to look at the
  project code to trace through type checker logic.
